                            <comment id="11794" author="jshomphe" created="Thu, 16 Dec 2004 05:56:02 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Here is a full stack trace:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;org.springframework.jdbc.UncategorizedSQLException: (executing PreparedStatementCallback &lt;span class=&quot;error&quot;&gt;&amp;#91;org.springframework.jdbc.core.JdbcTemplate$SimplePreparedStatementCreator@2e533a&amp;#93;&lt;/span&gt;): encountered SQLException &lt;span class=&quot;error&quot;&gt;&amp;#91;Invalid column type&amp;#93;&lt;/span&gt;; nested exception is java.sql.SQLException: Invalid column type&lt;br/&gt;
java.sql.SQLException: Invalid column type&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="11810" author="juergen.hoeller" created="Sun, 19 Dec 2004 03:41:55 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;The only way around this is to specify the SQL type of the NULL value. Up to Spring 1.1.3, you need to use the query version with a custom PreparedStatementSetter for this.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;As a convenience, I&apos;ve just added overloaded &quot;queryForList&quot;/&quot;queryForObject&quot;/&quot;queryForLong&quot;/&quot;queryForInt&quot; methods with an arg types int array, analogous to what we already had for &quot;update&quot;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Feel free to give a nightly snapshot a try!&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Juergen&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
